<!--
  Chapter 7 — Categorical Syllogisms
  Drafted in passes due to token-budget constraints.

  PROGRESS:
  - §7.1 (Standard Form Syllogisms): drafted.
  - §7.2 (Diagramming a Syllogism): drafted.
  - §7.3 (Common Validity Patterns and Failure Points): drafted.
  - §7.4 (Mood and Figure): drafted.
  - §7.5 (Putting Prose Arguments into Syllogism Form): drafted.
  - §7.6 (Where We're Headed): drafted.
  - Chapter summary, key terms, and end-of-chapter exercises: drafted.

  Diagram conventions (per the lead author's hand-drawn reference):
  - 3-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at bottom-left, P at
    bottom-right.
  - Eight numbered regions:
      1 = S only
      2 = S-and-P overlap, not M
      3 = P only
      4 = outside all three
      5 = S-and-M overlap, not P
      6 = S, P, and M overlap (center)
      7 = P-and-M overlap, not S
      8 = M only
  - 2-circle diagram for the conclusion uses the standard 4-area
    numbering from Chapter 6 (1 = S only; 2 = S-and-P overlap;
    3 = P only; 4 = outside both).
  - Validity testing: the premise diagram is a 3-circle; the
    conclusion diagram is a 2-circle; both share S on the left
    and P on the right at the bottom. The validity check is
    whether the marks the conclusion would put on its 2-circle
    diagram are already present in the premise diagram, mapped
    through the correspondence:
      Conclusion area 1 ↔ premise areas 1 and 5
      Conclusion area 2 ↔ premise areas 2 and 6
      Conclusion area 3 ↔ premise areas 3 and 7
      Conclusion area 4 ↔ premise areas 4 and 8

  Validity checks by conclusion form:
  - A: are BOTH areas 1 and 5 shaded in the premise diagram?
  - E: are BOTH areas 2 and 6 shaded in the premise diagram?
  - I: is there an X in EITHER area 1 or 5 of the premise diagram
       (not floating between, since that wouldn't commit to one)?
  - O: is there an X in EITHER area 2 or 6 of the premise diagram?

  Mood and figure are deferred to a later section in this chapter
  as the alternate encoding suitable for blind students. The Venn-
  diagram method is the primary technique.

  Voice: matter-of-fact, declarative, real-world examples where
  they land. Continues conventions from Chapter 6.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-categorical-syllogisms">

  <title>Categorical Syllogisms</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-categorical-syllogisms-intro">
    <p>
      Chapter 6 gave us the basic units of categorical logic: the
      four standard form propositions A, E, I, O, with their Venn
      diagrams, immediate inferences, and translation patterns.
      This chapter combines those propositions into arguments and
      gives us a procedure for evaluating those arguments for
      validity.
    </p>
    <p>
      The shape of argument we evaluate is the <term>categorical
      syllogism</term>: a three-statement argument with two
      premises and a conclusion, all standard-form categorical
      propositions, sharing exactly three terms among them. This
      is not every argument we will ever care about, but it is a
      surprising number of them. Once we have the procedure for
      evaluating syllogisms, we will have answered the first
      formal validity question this book promised.
    </p>
    <p>
      The procedure is geometric. We draw two diagrams: a
      three-circle Venn diagram representing the premises, and a
      two-circle Venn diagram representing what the conclusion
      claims. The syllogism is valid if the premise diagram
      already shows what the conclusion claims; invalid otherwise.
      Mood and figure — an alternate notation worth learning, and
      necessary as an accessible alternative for readers who do
      not work visually — appears later in the chapter as a
      second tool that does the same evaluative job.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-standard-form-syllogisms">
    <title>Standard Form Syllogisms</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Before we can evaluate a syllogism, we have to know what
        one looks like in standard form. A categorical syllogism
        is in <term>standard form</term> when (i) every statement
        in it is a standard form categorical proposition (A, E, I,
        or O); (ii) it has exactly two premises and a conclusion;
        (iii) the three statements use exactly three terms in
        total, each appearing twice; and (iv) the major premise is
        listed first, the minor premise second, the conclusion
        third.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-three-terms">
      <title>Three terms: major, minor, middle</title>
      <p>
        A categorical syllogism contains exactly three category
        terms, each appearing in exactly two of the three
        statements.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>major term</term> is the predicate of the
            conclusion. We label it <em>P</em>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>minor term</term> is the subject of the
            conclusion. We label it <em>S</em>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>middle term</term> is the term that appears
            in both premises but not in the conclusion. We label
            it <em>M</em>. The middle term's job is to connect
            the major and minor terms; it disappears from the
            conclusion because the syllogism has used it up making
            the connection.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The conclusion gives us S and P; the premises share M
        with the conclusion's terms.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-major-minor-premises">
      <title>The major and minor premises</title>
      <p>
        With S, P, and M identified, we name the two premises by
        which conclusion-term each one shares with the conclusion:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>major premise</term> is the premise that
            contains the major term P. (It also contains the
            middle term M, since each premise shares the middle
            term with the other premise.)
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The <term>minor premise</term> is the premise that
            contains the minor term S. (It also contains M.)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        In standard form, the major premise is written first, the
        minor premise second, and the conclusion third. The order
        is not part of what makes the syllogism logically work
        (the same premises in either order have the same logical
        force), but it is part of the standard format we use to
        present and evaluate syllogisms.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-syllogism-anatomy">
        <title>Anatomy of a syllogism</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Consider the syllogism:</p>
          <p>P1: All ozone molecules are good absorbers of UV rays.</p>
          <p>P2: All ozone molecules are substances destroyed by chlorine.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Some substances destroyed by chlorine are good absorbers of UV rays.</p>
          <p>The conclusion identifies the major and minor terms:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><p><alert>S (minor):</alert> substances destroyed by chlorine.</p></li>
            <li><p><alert>P (major):</alert> good absorbers of UV rays.</p></li>
          </ul>
          <p>The remaining term is the middle term:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><p><alert>M (middle):</alert> ozone molecules.</p></li>
          </ul>
          <p>P1 contains the major term and the middle term — it is the major premise. P2 contains the minor term and the middle term — it is the minor premise. The order is correct for standard form.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-validity-procedure-overview">
      <title>The validity procedure: two diagrams</title>
      <p>
        To evaluate a categorical syllogism for validity, we draw
        two diagrams and compare them.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>The premise diagram</alert> is a three-circle
            Venn diagram. The S circle is at the bottom left; the
            P circle is at the bottom right; the M circle is at
            the top, overlapping both. We mark this diagram to
            represent what the two premises claim.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>The conclusion diagram</alert> is a two-circle
            Venn diagram, identical in form to the diagrams from
            Chapter 6. The S circle is on the left; the P circle
            is on the right. We mark this diagram to represent
            what the conclusion claims.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The syllogism is valid if everything claimed in the
        conclusion diagram is already claimed by the premise
        diagram. The syllogism is invalid if the conclusion
        diagram requires something the premise diagram does not
        already show.
      </p>
      <p>
        The procedure, step by step:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Identify S, P, and M from the conclusion and premises.</p></li>
        <li><p>Draw the three-circle premise diagram with S, P, M positioned as described above.</p></li>
        <li><p>Mark the premises on the premise diagram, one at a time. Universal premises are shaded; particular premises get an X. (Important: shade universal premises <em>first</em>; particulars second. Shading first sometimes constrains where an X must go.)</p></li>
        <li><p>Draw the two-circle conclusion diagram and mark it with what the conclusion claims.</p></li>
        <li><p>Compare. Does the premise diagram already show what the conclusion diagram requires?</p></li>
      </ol>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-three-circle-numbering">
      <title>The eight regions of the three-circle diagram</title>
      <p>
        The three-circle premise diagram has eight regions, each
        of which we will refer to by number throughout the
        remainder of the chapter. The numbering convention,
        matching the description in the alt text of every diagram
        we draw:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>Area 1:</alert> inside S only — not in P, not in M.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 2:</alert> inside S and P but not M.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 3:</alert> inside P only — not in S, not in M.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 4:</alert> outside all three circles.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 5:</alert> inside S and M but not P.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 6:</alert> inside all three (the center).</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 7:</alert> inside P and M but not S.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Area 8:</alert> inside M only — not in S, not in P.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <figure xml:id="fig-three-circle-numbering">
        <caption>The standard three-circle Venn diagram with the eight regions numbered.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-three-circle-numbering" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram. The S circle is at the
              bottom left. The P circle is at the bottom right.
              The M circle is at the top, overlapping both. The
              eight regions are numbered as follows: area 1 is
              the part of S that is outside both P and M; area 2
              is the part of S and P that is outside M; area 3
              is the part of P that is outside both S and M;
              area 4 is the region outside all three circles;
              area 5 is the part of S and M that is outside P;
              area 6 is the center, inside all three; area 7 is
              the part of P and M that is outside S; area 8 is
              the part of M that is outside both S and P.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-comparing-diagrams">
      <title>Comparing the two diagrams: how the conclusion checks against the premises</title>
      <p>
        The conclusion's two-circle diagram has only four areas
        (1, 2, 3, 4), but those areas correspond to pairs of
        regions in the three-circle premise diagram. Each area of
        the conclusion's two-circle diagram covers two regions of
        the premise's three-circle diagram — the pair that differs
        only in whether M is included.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>Conclusion-diagram area 1 (S only) corresponds to premise-diagram areas <alert>1 and 5</alert>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Conclusion-diagram area 2 (the S-and-P overlap) corresponds to premise-diagram areas <alert>2 and 6</alert>.</p></li>
        <li><p>Conclusion-diagram area 3 (P only) corresponds to premise-diagram areas 3 and 7.</p></li>
        <li><p>Conclusion-diagram area 4 (outside both) corresponds to premise-diagram areas 4 and 8.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Validity, then, becomes a check: does the premise diagram
        already mark these paired regions in the way the
        conclusion's diagram requires?
      </p>
      <p>
        The check depends on the conclusion's form (A, E, I, or
        O). For each form, here is the question to ask of the
        premise diagram:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>A conclusion (All S are P).</alert> The
            conclusion shades area 1 of its two-circle diagram.
            Validity check: are <em>both</em> areas 1 <em>and</em>
            5 shaded in the premise diagram? If yes, the syllogism
            is valid. If either is unshaded, it is invalid.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>E conclusion (No S are P).</alert> The
            conclusion shades area 2 of its two-circle diagram.
            Validity check: are <em>both</em> areas 2 <em>and</em>
            6 shaded in the premise diagram? If yes, the syllogism
            is valid. If either is unshaded, it is invalid.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>I conclusion (Some S are P).</alert> The
            conclusion places an X in area 2 of its two-circle
            diagram. Validity check: is there an X in <em>area 2
            or area 6</em> of the premise diagram, definitely
            placed in one of those areas (not on a boundary
            between an in-the-conclusion-area region and an
            outside-it region)? If yes, the syllogism is valid.
            If no X is committed to either of those areas, it is
            invalid.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>O conclusion (Some S are not P).</alert> The
            conclusion places an X in area 1 of its two-circle
            diagram. Validity check: is there an X in <em>area 1
            or area 5</em> of the premise diagram, definitely
            placed in one of those areas? If yes, the syllogism
            is valid. If no X is committed to either of those
            areas, it is invalid.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        The pattern: for universal conclusions, we need
        <em>both</em> regions in the relevant pair to be shaded.
        For particular conclusions, we need an X <em>in either</em>
        of the regions in the relevant pair. The next section
        works through the procedure on actual syllogisms.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-diagramming-a-syllogism">
    <title>Diagramming a Syllogism</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        With the eight-region numbering and the conclusion-form
        validity checks from <xref ref="sec-standard-form-syllogisms"/>
        in hand, we can now actually mark a premise diagram. Each
        premise is a categorical proposition involving two of the
        three terms (S, P, M); each premise either shades some
        regions (if it is universal) or places an X (if it is
        particular). The point is not to memorize a list of
        regions. The point is to understand what the premise says
        and then mark that meaning on the diagram.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-subject-first-diagramming">
      <title>Start with the subject term</title>
      <p>
        A categorical premise first tells us which term we are
        talking about: the <em>subject</em> term. On the
        three-circle diagram, that subject term takes up four
        numbered areas. The predicate term then tells us which of
        those four areas matter.
      </p>
      <p>
        Take <q>All P are M.</q> The subject is P, so we begin
        with the four areas inside the P circle: areas 2, 3, 6,
        and 7. The predicate is M. Of those P areas, areas 6 and
        7 are also inside M. Areas 2 and 3 are P but not M.
      </p>
      <p>
        <q>All P are M</q> means every P is also an M. So there
        cannot be any P outside M. We shade areas 2 and 3. The
        only P areas left unshaded are areas 6 and 7, the parts
        of P that are also M.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-all-p-are-m-subject-first">
        <caption>All P are M: areas 2 and 3 are shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-all-p-are-m-subject-first" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. Areas 2, 3, 6,
              and 7 are inside the P circle. Areas 2 and 3 are
              shaded, showing that the part of P outside M is
              empty. Areas 6 and 7, the parts of P that are also
              inside M, are unshaded. Areas 1, 4, 5, and 8 are
              also unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              % Shade P outside M: areas 2 and 3
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Pright;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
                \fill[white] \Mtop;
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Notice what the S circle did. It split the P-outside-M
        region into two pieces: area 2 is inside S, and area 3 is
        outside S. But the premise did not mention S. It simply
        said that no P is outside M. So both pieces of P outside
        M have to be shaded.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-four-premise-forms-on-three-circles">
      <title>The four forms on a three-circle diagram</title>
      <p>
        The same subject-first thinking works for all four
        categorical forms.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>A propositions eliminate the subject outside the
        predicate.</alert> We just saw <q>All P are M.</q> Since
        P is the subject, the P circle is the starting place.
        Since the predicate is M, the forbidden region is P
        outside M. That is why areas 2 and 3 are shaded.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>E propositions eliminate the overlap.</alert> The
        premise <q>No right-wing hate mongers are socialists</q>
        has the form <q>No P are M.</q> The subject is P:
        right-wing hate mongers. The predicate is M: socialists.
        The premise says that nothing is both P and M. On the
        three-circle diagram, the P-and-M overlap is split into
        areas 6 and 7, so both are shaded.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-no-p-are-m-subject-first">
        <caption>No P are M: areas 6 and 7 are shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-no-p-are-m-subject-first" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. Areas 6 and 7
              are shaded. These two areas make up the overlap of P
              and M: area 6 is also inside S, and area 7 is
              outside S. Areas 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, and 8 are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              % Shade P and M overlap: areas 6 and 7
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Pright;
                \clip \Mtop;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        <alert>I propositions assert existence in the overlap.</alert>
        The premise <q>Some Americans are socialists</q> has the
        form <q>Some S are M.</q> The subject is S: Americans.
        The predicate is M: socialists. The premise says at least
        one thing is both S and M. On the three-circle diagram,
        the S-and-M overlap is areas 5 and 6. The premise does
        not say whether that thing is also P, so the X sits on
        the boundary between 5 and 6.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-some-s-are-m-boundary">
        <caption>Some S are M: an X is on the boundary between areas 5 and 6.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-some-s-are-m-boundary" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. An X lies on the
              boundary between areas 5 and 6. Areas 5 and 6 are
              the overlap of S and M. Area 5 is outside P; area 6
              is inside P. The boundary X means that something is
              in S and M, but the premise alone does not say
              whether it is outside P or inside P. No areas are
              shaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
              \node at (-0.35,0.35) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        <alert>O propositions assert existence in the subject
        outside the predicate.</alert> The premise <q>Some S are
        not M</q> starts with S as the subject. The relevant part
        of S is the part outside M. That region is split by the P
        circle into areas 1 and 2. The premise does not say
        whether the thing is P, so the X sits on the boundary
        between 1 and 2.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-some-s-are-not-m-boundary">
        <caption>Some S are not M: an X is on the boundary between areas 1 and 2.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-some-s-are-not-m-boundary" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. An X lies on the
              boundary between areas 1 and 2. Areas 1 and 2 are
              the part of S outside M. Area 1 is outside P; area
              2 is inside P. The boundary X means that something
              is in S and outside M, but the premise alone does
              not say whether it is outside P or inside P. No
              areas are shaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
              \node at (-0.55,-0.8) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-shade-before-particulars">
      <title>Shade before placing Xs</title>
      <p>
        Universal premises tell us that a region is empty.
        Particular premises tell us that something exists. When a
        syllogism has both kinds, mark the universal premises
        first. Shading can remove one of the candidate regions for
        an X, forcing the X into the only remaining place.
      </p>
      <p>
        The next worked example shows this. If we considered
        <q>Some Americans are socialists</q> by itself, the X
        would sit between areas 5 and 6. But another premise has
        already shaded area 6. Since an X cannot go in an empty
        region, the X is forced into area 5.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-example-EAE-1">
      <title>Worked Example 1: a valid syllogism (EAE-1)</title>
      <p>
        Consider the following syllogism, drawn from a science-fiction
        textbook example:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-eae-1-syllogism">
        <title>Tralfamadorians and human life</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: No alien creatures are creatures that would understand human life.</p>
          <p>P2: All Tralfamadorians are alien creatures.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: No Tralfamadorians are creatures that would understand human life.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Identify the terms from the conclusion. The minor term S
        is <em>Tralfamadorians</em>; the major term P is
        <em>creatures that would understand human life</em>. The
        middle term M is <em>alien creatures</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        P1 (<q>No alien creatures are creatures that would
        understand human life</q>) is an E proposition involving M
        and P. Its subject is M: alien creatures. Its predicate is
        P: creatures that would understand human life. The premise
        says that nothing is both M and P, so the M-and-P overlap
        is empty. On the three-circle diagram, that overlap is
        areas 6 and 7. Shade both.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2 (<q>All Tralfamadorians are alien creatures</q>) is an
        A proposition involving S and M. Its subject is S:
        Tralfamadorians. Its predicate is M: alien creatures. The
        premise says that every S is inside M, so there are no
        S's outside M. On the three-circle diagram, S outside M is
        split into areas 1 and 2. Shade both.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both premises are universals, so this premise diagram only
        needs shading. No X marks are placed.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-eae-1-premises">
        <caption>The premise diagram for EAE-1: areas 1, 2, 6, and 7 are shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-eae-1-premises" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. In this example,
              S is Tralfamadorians, P is creatures that would
              understand human life, and M is alien creatures.
              Areas 6 and 7 are shaded — these are the overlap of
              M and P, both with S (area 6, the center) and
              without S (area 7). Areas 1 and 2 are also shaded —
              these are the part of S that is outside M, both
              outside P (area 1) and inside P (area 2). Areas 3,
              4, 5, and 8 are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              % Shade areas 1 and 2 (S minus M)
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
                \fill[white] \Mtop;
              \end{scope}
              % Shade areas 6 and 7 (the M-and-P overlap)
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Pright;
                \clip \Mtop;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <figure xml:id="fig-eae-1-conclusion">
        <caption>The conclusion diagram for EAE-1: area 2 is shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-eae-1-conclusion" width="50%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram for the conclusion, with S
              on the left and P on the right. In this example, S is
              Tralfamadorians and P is creatures that would
              understand human life. The overlap of S and P, area
              2, is shaded. This represents the conclusion <q>No S
              are P.</q> Areas 1, 3, and 4 are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \def\Pright{(0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              % Shade area 2 (the S-and-P overlap)
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \clip \Pright;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.35,-1.15) {$S$};
              \node at (1.35,-1.15) {$P$};
              \node at (-0.85,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (0.85,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (0,-1.65) {\small 4};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Now check the conclusion. The conclusion is an E
        proposition: <q>No S are P.</q> The validity check from
        <xref ref="sec-standard-form-syllogisms"/> says: are
        <em>both</em> areas 2 and 6 shaded?
      </p>
      <p>
        Area 2: shaded (by P2). Area 6: shaded (by P1). Both
        regions are shaded. The premise diagram shows what the
        conclusion claims. The syllogism is <alert>valid</alert>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-example-EIO-2">
      <title>Worked Example 2: a syllogism with a particular premise (EIO-2)</title>
      <p>
        The next example shows what happens when one premise is
        particular and the universal premise has already shaded
        one of the X's candidate regions.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-eio-2-syllogism">
        <title>Right-wing hate mongers, socialists, and Americans</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: No right-wing hate mongers are socialists.</p>
          <p>P2: Some Americans are socialists.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Some Americans are not right-wing hate mongers.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        From the conclusion: S is <em>Americans</em>; P is
        <em>right-wing hate mongers</em>. M is the term in both
        premises but not the conclusion: <em>socialists</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        P1 (<q>No right-wing hate mongers are socialists</q>) is
        an E proposition involving P and M. Its subject is P:
        right-wing hate mongers. Its predicate is M: socialists.
        The premise says that nothing is both P and M, so the
        P-and-M overlap is empty. On the three-circle diagram,
        that overlap is areas 6 and 7. Shade both.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2 (<q>Some Americans are socialists</q>) is an I
        proposition involving S and M. Its subject is S:
        Americans. Its predicate is M: socialists. The premise
        says that at least one thing is both S and M, so the X
        belongs in the S-and-M overlap. That overlap is areas 5
        and 6. But area 6 is <em>already shaded</em> by P1:
        declared empty. So the X cannot go there. It must go in
        area 5.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the practical reason for shading universals first.
        If we had drawn the X first as a boundary X between 5 and
        6, we would have had to revisit it after shading P1. By
        shading first, the X's placement is forced immediately.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-eio-2-premises">
        <caption>The premise diagram for EIO-2: areas 6 and 7 shaded; X in area 5.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-eio-2-premises" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. In this example,
              S is Americans, P is right-wing hate mongers, and M
              is socialists. Areas 6 and 7 are shaded — these are
              the overlap of M and P, both with S (area 6, the
              center) and without S (area 7). An X is placed in
              area 5, which is the overlap of S and M outside P.
              Areas 1, 2, 3, 4, and 8 are unshaded and unmarked.
              Although the I premise alone would have allowed the X
              to be in area 5 or 6, the shading from the E premise
              forces the X into area 5.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              % Shade areas 6 and 7 (the M-and-P overlap)
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Pright;
                \clip \Mtop;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.55) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
              % X in area 5
              \node at (-0.85,0.2) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <figure xml:id="fig-eio-2-conclusion">
        <caption>The conclusion diagram for EIO-2: X in area 1.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-eio-2-conclusion" width="50%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram for the conclusion, with S
              on the left and P on the right. In this example, S is
              Americans and P is right-wing hate mongers. An X is
              placed in area 1, the part of S outside P. This
              represents the conclusion <q>Some S are not P.</q>
              No areas are shaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \def\Pright{(0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.35,-1.15) {$S$};
              \node at (1.35,-1.15) {$P$};
              \node at (-0.85,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (0.85,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (0,-1.65) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.75,0.35) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Now check the conclusion. The conclusion is O: <q>Some S
        are not P.</q> The validity check says: is there an X in
        either area 1 or area 5 of the premise diagram?
      </p>
      <p>
        There is an X in area 5. The premise diagram shows what
        the conclusion claims. The syllogism is
        <alert>valid</alert>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-worked-example-iii-boundary">
      <title>Worked Example 3: all particulars and boundary Xs</title>
      <p>
        Sometimes nothing constrains a particular premise's X.
        When that happens, the X stays on the boundary between
        its two candidate regions. An all-particular syllogism is
        a clean way to see this.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-iii-boundary-syllogism">
        <title>Two uncommitted Xs</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: Some <em>Picard</em> fans are not <em>Star Trek: Deep Space Nine</em> fans.</p>
          <p>P2: Some <em>Picard</em> fans are <em>Star Trek: Discovery</em> fans.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Some <em>Star Trek: Discovery</em> fans are not <em>Star Trek: Deep Space Nine</em> fans.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        From the conclusion: S is <em>Star Trek: Discovery</em>
        fans; P is <em>Star Trek: Deep Space Nine</em> fans. The
        middle term M is <em>Picard</em> fans.
      </p>
      <p>
        P1 (<q>Some <em>Picard</em> fans are not <em>Star Trek:
        Deep Space Nine</em> fans</q>) is an O proposition. Its
        subject is M: <em>Picard</em> fans. Its predicate is P:
        <em>Star Trek: Deep Space Nine</em> fans. The premise says
        that at least one M is outside P. On the three-circle
        diagram, M outside P is areas 5 and 8. Since neither area
        is shaded, the X goes on the boundary between 5 and 8.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2 (<q>Some <em>Picard</em> fans are <em>Star Trek:
        Discovery</em> fans</q>) is an I proposition. Its subject
        is M: <em>Picard</em> fans. Its predicate is S:
        <em>Star Trek: Discovery</em> fans. The premise says that
        at least one M is also S. On the three-circle diagram, M
        and S overlap in areas 5 and 6. Since neither area is
        shaded, this X goes on the boundary between 5 and 6.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-iii-boundary-premises">
        <caption>The premise diagram for the all-particular example: one X on the boundary between areas 5 and 8, and one X on the boundary between areas 5 and 6.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-iii-boundary-premises" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. In this example,
              S is <em>Star Trek: Discovery</em> fans, P is
              <em>Star Trek: Deep Space Nine</em> fans, and M is
              <em>Picard</em> fans. One X lies on the boundary
              between areas 5 and 8, representing <q>Some
              <em>Picard</em> fans are not <em>Star Trek: Deep
              Space Nine</em> fans.</q> That X is somewhere in M
              outside P, but it is not committed to being inside or
              outside S. A second X lies on the boundary between
              areas 5 and 6, representing <q>Some <em>Picard</em>
              fans are <em>Star Trek: Discovery</em> fans.</q>
              That X is somewhere in the overlap of S and M, but
              it is not committed to being inside or outside P. No
              regions are shaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
              % Boundary Xs
              \node at (-0.55,0.9) {$\times$};
              \node at (-0.35,0.35) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <figure xml:id="fig-iii-boundary-conclusion">
        <caption>The conclusion diagram for the all-particular example: X in area 1.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-iii-boundary-conclusion" width="50%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram for the conclusion, with S
              on the left and P on the right. In this example, S is
              <em>Star Trek: Discovery</em> fans and P is
              <em>Star Trek: Deep Space Nine</em> fans. An X is
              placed in area 1, the part of S outside P. This
              represents the conclusion <q>Some <em>Star Trek:
              Discovery</em> fans are not <em>Star Trek: Deep
              Space Nine</em> fans.</q> No areas are shaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \def\Pright{(0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.35,-1.15) {$S$};
              \node at (1.35,-1.15) {$P$};
              \node at (-0.85,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (0.85,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (0,-1.65) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.75,0.35) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        For the validity check, an uncommitted X on a boundary
        does <em>not</em> satisfy the requirement that the X be
        definitely in one of the conclusion's required regions.
        The premises must commit the X to one of the regions the
        conclusion requires. If the X is on a boundary between a
        region the conclusion requires and a region it does not,
        the syllogism is invalid: the premises haven't done
        enough work to settle the issue the conclusion claims to
        settle.
      </p>
      <p>
        In this example, the conclusion requires an X in area 1
        or area 5 of the premise diagram. The premise diagram has
        no X in area 1. It has two boundary Xs that touch area 5,
        but neither is definitely in area 5. So the premise
        diagram does not show what the conclusion claims. The
        syllogism is <alert>invalid</alert>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-validity-patterns-failure-points">
    <title>Common Validity Patterns and Failure Points</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        With the diagramming procedure from
        <xref ref="sec-diagramming-a-syllogism"/> and the
        conclusion-form validity checks from
        <xref ref="sec-standard-form-syllogisms"/>, you can in
        principle evaluate any standard-form categorical syllogism
        for validity. In practice, a few patterns come up over and
        over — both valid patterns that are worth recognizing on
        sight, and failure points that are worth being able to
        diagnose without redoing the whole diagram. This section
        works through three diagrammed cases and one summarized
        failure point.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-aee-2-valid">
      <title>A clean valid case (AEE-2)</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-aee-2-syllogism">
        <title>Death penalty opponents and Trump supporters</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: All morally righteous people are death penalty opponents.</p>
          <p>P2: No Trump supporters are death penalty opponents.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: No Trump supporters are morally righteous people.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        From the conclusion, S is <em>Trump supporters</em>; P is
        <em>morally righteous people</em>; M is the middle term,
        <em>death penalty opponents</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        P1 (<q>All morally righteous people are death penalty
        opponents</q>) is an A proposition involving P and M, with
        P as the subject and M as the predicate. <q>All P are M</q>
        shades the part of P that is outside M, which is areas 2
        and 3. Mark them shaded.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2 (<q>No Trump supporters are death penalty opponents</q>)
        is an E proposition involving S and M. <q>No S are M</q>
        shades the overlap of S and M, which is areas 5 and 6.
        Mark them shaded.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both premises are universal, so the X mark step does not
        apply. The premise diagram is complete.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-aee-2-premises">
        <caption>The premise diagram for AEE-2: areas 2, 3, 5, and 6 are shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-aee-2-premises" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. Areas 2 and 3
              are shaded — the part of P outside M, both inside S
              (area 2) and outside S (area 3). Areas 5 and 6 are
              also shaded — the overlap of S and M, both outside
              P (area 5) and inside P (area 6). Areas 1, 4, 7,
              and 8 are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Pright;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
                \fill[white] \Mtop;
              \end{scope}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \clip \Mtop;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        The conclusion is E: <q>No S are P.</q> The validity check
        asks whether <em>both</em> areas 2 and 6 are shaded.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-aee-2-conclusion">
        <caption>The conclusion diagram for AEE-2: area 2 shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-aee-2-conclusion" width="45%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram with S, Trump supporters,
              on the left and P, morally righteous people, on the
              right. Area 2, the overlap of S and P, is shaded.
              Areas 1, 3, and 4 are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \def\Pright{(0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \clip \Pright;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.35,-1.15) {$S$};
              \node at (1.35,-1.15) {$P$};
              \node at (-0.85,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (0.85,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (0,-1.65) {\small 4};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Area 2 was shaded by P1; area 6 was shaded by P2. Both
        shaded. The premise diagram shows exactly what the
        conclusion diagram requires. The syllogism is
        <alert>valid</alert>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-eea-2-invalid">
      <title>An invalid case where the conclusion overreaches (EEA-2)</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-eea-2-syllogism">
        <title>Vegetarians, meat eaters, and consistent thinkers</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: No vegetarians are meat eaters.</p>
          <p>P2: No consistent thinkers are meat eaters.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: All consistent thinkers are vegetarians.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        From the conclusion, S is <em>consistent thinkers</em>;
        P is <em>vegetarians</em>; M is the middle term,
        <em>meat eaters</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        P1 (<q>No vegetarians are meat eaters</q>) is an E
        proposition involving P and M. <q>No P are M</q> shades
        the overlap of P and M, which is areas 6 and 7.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2 (<q>No consistent thinkers are meat eaters</q>) is an E
        proposition involving S and M. <q>No S are M</q> shades
        the overlap of S and M, which is areas 5 and 6. Area 6 is
        already shaded; we just shade area 5 in addition.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-eea-2-premises">
        <caption>The premise diagram for EEA-2: areas 5, 6, and 7 are shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-eea-2-premises" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. Areas 5, 6, and
              7 are shaded — the entire portion of M that
              overlaps either S or P. Area 8, the part of M
              outside both S and P, is unshaded. Areas 1, 2, 3,
              and 4 are also unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Pright;
                \clip \Mtop;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \clip \Mtop;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        The conclusion is A: <q>All S are P.</q> The validity
        check asks whether <em>both</em> areas 1 and 5 are shaded.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-eea-2-conclusion">
        <caption>The conclusion diagram for EEA-2: area 1 shaded.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-eea-2-conclusion" width="45%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram with S, consistent
              thinkers, on the left and P, vegetarians, on the
              right. Area 1, the part of S outside P, is shaded.
              Areas 2, 3, and 4 are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \def\Pright{(0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Sleft;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
                \fill[white] \Pright;
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.35,-1.15) {$S$};
              \node at (1.35,-1.15) {$P$};
              \node at (-0.85,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 2};
              \node at (0.85,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (0,-1.65) {\small 4};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        Area 5 is shaded (by P2). Area 1 is not shaded by either
        premise. The premise diagram does not show what the
        conclusion diagram requires. The syllogism is
        <alert>invalid</alert>.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a useful pattern to see clearly. The two negative
        premises tell us about emptiness in the M-area; they say
        nothing about how S relates to P outside of M. The
        conclusion then leaps to a positive claim relating S and P
        directly. There is no path from <q>nothing in the S-and-M
        overlap</q> and <q>nothing in the P-and-M overlap</q> to
        <q>everything in S is in P.</q>
        The conclusion is overreaching the premises. This is a
        general lesson: <alert>two negative premises rarely give
        you what you need for a positive conclusion.</alert>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-aai-3-existential-import">
      <title>The modern-vs-Aristotelian case (AAI-3)</title>
      <p>
        The next case is the one most likely to feel paradoxical,
        because it depends on the existential-commitment
        distinction we drew in
        <xref ref="sec-existential-commitment"/>. On the modern
        interpretation, the syllogism is invalid. On the
        Aristotelian interpretation, it is valid.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-aai-3-syllogism">
        <title>Ozone molecules</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: All ozone molecules are good absorbers of UV rays.</p>
          <p>P2: All ozone molecules are substances destroyed by chlorine.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Some substances destroyed by chlorine are good absorbers of UV rays.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        From the conclusion, S is <em>substances destroyed by
        chlorine</em>; P is <em>good absorbers of UV rays</em>; M
        is <em>ozone molecules</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        P1 (<q>All M are P</q>) shades areas 5 and 8.
      </p>
      <p>
        P2 (<q>All M are S</q>) shades areas 7 and 8. Area 8 is
        already shaded by P1.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both premises are universal. After shading, areas 5, 7,
        and 8 are shaded. Area 6 — the overlap of all three
        circles, the only remaining piece of M — is the only
        place where any ozone molecules could exist if they exist
        at all.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-aai-3-premises">
        <caption>The premise diagram for AAI-3: areas 5, 7, and 8 shaded; area 6 is the only remaining region of M.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-aai-3-premises" width="60%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A three-circle Venn diagram with M at top, S at
              bottom-left, and P at bottom-right. Areas 5, 7, and
              8 are shaded — these together exhaust the part of M
              that is outside the S-and-P overlap. Area 6, the overlap of all
              three circles, is unshaded. Areas 1, 2, 3, and 4
              are also unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Pright{(0.7,-0.4) circle (1.3)}
              \def\Mtop{(0,0.6) circle (1.3)}
              \begin{scope}
                \clip \Mtop;
                \fill[gray!40] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
                \begin{scope}
                  \clip \Sleft;
                  \clip \Pright;
                  \fill[white] (-3,-3) rectangle (3,3);
                \end{scope}
              \end{scope}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \draw \Mtop;
              \node at (-1.7,-1.4) {$S$};
              \node at (1.7,-1.4) {$P$};
              \node at (0,1.9) {$M$};
              \node at (-1.3,-0.7) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,-1.0) {\small 2};
              \node at (1.3,-0.7) {\small 3};
              \node at (-2.1,-1.7) {\small 4};
              \node at (-0.85,0.35) {\small 5};
              \node at (0,0) {\small 6};
              \node at (0.85,0.35) {\small 7};
              \node at (0,1.3) {\small 8};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        The conclusion is I: <q>Some S are P.</q> The validity
        check asks whether there is an X in area 2 or area 6 of
        the premise diagram.
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-aai-3-conclusion">
        <caption>The conclusion diagram for AAI-3: X in area 2.</caption>
        <image xml:id="image-aai-3-conclusion" width="45%">
          <description>
            <p>
              A two-circle Venn diagram with S, substances
              destroyed by chlorine, on the left and P, good
              absorbers of UV rays, on the right. An X appears in
              area 2, the overlap of S and P. Areas 1, 3, and 4
              are unshaded.
            </p>
          </description>
          <latex-image>
            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
              \def\Sleft{(-0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \def\Pright{(0.55,0) circle (1.2)}
              \draw \Sleft;
              \draw \Pright;
              \node at (-1.35,-1.15) {$S$};
              \node at (1.35,-1.15) {$P$};
              \node at (-0.85,0) {\small 1};
              \node at (0,0.35) {\small 2};
              \node at (0.85,0) {\small 3};
              \node at (0,-1.65) {\small 4};
              \node at (0,-0.05) {$\times$};
            \end{tikzpicture}
          </latex-image>
        </image>
      </figure>
      <p>
        On the modern interpretation, no X has been placed
        anywhere. Universal premises do not carry existential
        commitment. <q>All M are P</q> does not assert that any M
        exists. The conclusion diagram requires an X, but the
        premise diagram has only shading; nothing commits to the
        existence of any ozone molecule. So no X is in area 2 or
        6. The syllogism is
        <alert>invalid on the modern interpretation</alert>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Suppose we ask a different question: <em>what would
        happen if at least one ozone molecule actually exists?</em>
        We can answer that question directly on the diagram. Area
        6 is the only unshaded region of the M circle, so any
        existing ozone molecule has to be there. Place an X in
        area 6. Now run the validity check for the I conclusion:
        is there an X in area 2 or 6? Yes — there is an X in area
        6. Under the assumption that at least one ozone molecule
        exists, the syllogism is valid.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is the conceptual move worth keeping. Whenever a
        syllogism comes out invalid on the modern interpretation
        because no X has been placed, you can ask: <em>would
        adding an X to the diagram — that is, asserting that at
        least one entity in the relevant category actually exists
        — change the verdict?</em> Place the X and run the check.
        If the syllogism would be valid <em>given</em> that
        existence claim, then the modern verdict of invalidity is
        tracking the existential-commitment question and nothing
        else. We can easily check if existence makes a difference,
        but on the modern interpretation, we have to make that
        commitment explicit, outside of any universal claims.
      </p>
      <p>
        Aristotelian or classical syllogistic logic is more fully
        explored in <xref ref="appendix-aristotelian-categorical"/>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-boundary-x-summary">
      <title>The boundary-X failure point (summarized)</title>
      <p>
        One more failure pattern is worth describing in words even
        though we will not rediagram it in full here. It comes up
        whenever both premises are particular.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider OIO-2:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-oio-2-syllogism">
        <title>Picard fans, DS9 fans, Discovery fans</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: Some <q>Picard</q> fans are not <q>Star Trek Deep Space 9</q> fans.</p>
          <p>P2: Some <q>Picard</q> fans are <q>Star Trek Discovery</q> fans.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Some <q>Star Trek Discovery</q> fans are not <q>Star Trek Deep Space 9</q> fans.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Mapping to standard letters: S is <em>Discovery fans</em>;
        P is <em>DS9 fans</em>; M is <em>Picard fans</em>. Both
        premises are particular: P1 places an X in M outside P
        (areas 5 or 8), and P2 places an X in the overlap of S and
        M (areas 5 or 6). Neither premise is shaded by anything,
        because neither premise is universal. So both X marks sit
        on their boundaries, uncommitted.
      </p>
      <p>
        The conclusion (O) requires an X in area 1 or area 5,
        committed to one of those regions. P2's X is on the
        boundary between 5 and 6. P1's X is on the boundary
        between 5 and 8. Neither X is committed to area 5; either
        could be in area 6 or area 8 instead. The premise diagram
        does not show what the conclusion requires. The syllogism
        is <alert>invalid</alert>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The general lesson here is stronger than <q>often
        invalid</q>: <alert>two particular premises never give you
        a valid syllogism.</alert> The reasoning is structural.
        Particular premises produce X marks; X marks need
        universal-premise shading to be committed to a single
        region. With no universals on offer, both X marks sit on
        boundaries, uncommitted, and the validity check fails for
        any particular conclusion. A universal conclusion is also
        impossible from two particular premises, since universal
        conclusions require shading and two particular premises
        provide no shading. So if both premises are particular,
        the syllogism is invalid no matter what the conclusion is.
        Spot the two-particular-premises pattern and you can stop
        diagramming.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-mood-and-figure">
    <title>Mood and Figure</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The Venn-diagram method is the primary technique in this
        chapter. It shows why a syllogism is valid or invalid. But
        there is also a compact text notation for the same
        structure: <term>mood and figure</term>. Mood and figure
        let us encode a syllogism as a short label such as
        <q>EAE-1</q> or <q>AEE-2.</q> Once a syllogism is encoded
        this way, we can compare it with a validity table.
      </p>
      <p>
        This notation is especially useful as an accessible
        alternative to diagrams. A reader who is not working
        visually can identify the proposition forms, identify the
        position of the middle term, and use the table below to
        reach the same validity verdict the Venn diagram would
        give.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-mood">
      <title>Mood</title>
      <p>
        The <term>mood</term> of a categorical syllogism is the
        sequence of its three proposition forms, in standard-form
        order: major premise, minor premise, conclusion. Each
        statement contributes one letter: A, E, I, or O.
      </p>
      <p>
        Consider the first worked example from this chapter:
      </p>
      <p>P1: No alien creatures are creatures that would understand human life.</p>
      <p>P2: All Tralfamadorians are alien creatures.</p>
      <p>C: No Tralfamadorians are creatures that would understand human life.</p>
      <p>
        P1 is E, P2 is A, and C is E. So the mood is
        <alert>EAE</alert>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Mood records only the forms of the three statements. It
        does not yet tell us where the middle term appears. For
        that, we need figure.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-figure">
      <title>Figure</title>
      <p>
        The <term>figure</term> of a categorical syllogism records
        the position of the middle term M in the two premises.
        The conclusion is always S-P in standard form, so the
        conclusion does not determine the figure. The figure is
        determined entirely by the two premises.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are four possible figures. In the patterns below,
        X-Y means that X is the subject term and Y is the predicate
        term of that premise.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><p><alert>Figure 1:</alert> major premise M-P; minor premise S-M.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Figure 2:</alert> major premise P-M; minor premise S-M.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Figure 3:</alert> major premise M-P; minor premise M-S.</p></li>
        <li><p><alert>Figure 4:</alert> major premise P-M; minor premise M-S.</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        In the Tralfamadorian example above, P1 is <q>No M are
        P</q> and P2 is <q>All S are M.</q> That is Figure 1:
        major premise M-P, minor premise S-M. Since the mood is
        EAE and the figure is 1, the full label is
        <alert>EAE-1</alert>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-identifying-mood-figure">
      <title>How to identify mood and figure</title>
      <p>
        Use the same first steps you use for the Venn method.
        First identify the conclusion. The subject of the
        conclusion is S; the predicate of the conclusion is P.
        The remaining term, the one that appears in both premises
        but not in the conclusion, is M. Then identify the form of
        each statement and the position of M in the premises.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-identifying-aee-2">
        <title>Identifying AEE-2</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: All morally righteous people are death penalty opponents.</p>
          <p>P2: No Trump supporters are death penalty opponents.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: No Trump supporters are morally righteous people.</p>
          <p>
            From the conclusion, S is <em>Trump supporters</em>
            and P is <em>morally righteous people</em>. The middle
            term M is <em>death penalty opponents</em>.
          </p>
          <p>
            P1 has the form <q>All P are M</q>, so the first mood
            letter is A. P2 has the form <q>No S are M</q>, so the
            second mood letter is E. The conclusion has the form
            <q>No S are P</q>, so the third mood letter is E. The
            mood is AEE.
          </p>
          <p>
            The major premise is P-M and the minor premise is S-M.
            That is Figure 2. The full label is
            <alert>AEE-2</alert>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-modern-valid-forms">
      <title>The modern-valid forms</title>
      <p>
        The following table gives the valid categorical syllogism
        forms on the modern interpretation used in this book. If a
        standard-form syllogism has one of these mood-and-figure
        labels, it is valid. If it does not, it is invalid.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Figure 1:</alert> AAA-1, AII-1, EAE-1, EIO-1.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Figure 2:</alert> AEE-2, AOO-2, EAE-2, EIO-2.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Figure 3:</alert> AII-3, EIO-3, IAI-3, OAO-3.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Figure 4:</alert> AEE-4, EIO-4, IAI-4.
      </p>
      <p>
        The table is deliberately modern. Forms that depend on
        existential commitment from universal premises are not
        listed. For example, AAI-3 was discussed in the previous
        section: it becomes valid if we add the existence claim,
        but it is invalid on the modern interpretation because the
        universal premises alone do not place an X anywhere in the
        diagram.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-mood-figure-examples">
      <title>Checking examples from the chapter</title>
      <p>
        Mood and figure should agree with the Venn-diagram verdict.
        We can check that against examples we have already worked.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>EAE-1.</alert> The Tralfamadorian example has mood
        EAE and Figure 1. EAE-1 appears in the valid-form table, so
        the syllogism is valid. That matches the Venn diagram.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>EIO-2.</alert> The Americans/socialists/right-wing
        hate mongers example has mood EIO and Figure 2. EIO-2
        appears in the valid-form table, so the syllogism is
        valid. Again, that matches the Venn diagram.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>EEA-2.</alert> The vegetarians/meat eaters/consistent
        thinkers example has mood EEA and Figure 2. EEA-2 does not
        appear in the valid-form table, so the syllogism is
        invalid. That matches the Venn diagram, where the conclusion
        overreached the premises.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>AAI-3.</alert> The ozone example has mood AAI and
        Figure 3. AAI-3 does not appear in the modern-valid table,
        so it is invalid on the modern interpretation. That matches
        the Venn diagram: no X is placed by the universal premises.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-mood-figure-limits">
      <title>What the table does and does not do</title>
      <p>
        The table is a shortcut for evaluation, not a replacement
        for understanding. It tells you whether a standard-form
        syllogism is valid once you have correctly identified its
        mood and figure. It does not explain why the form is valid
        or invalid. The Venn-diagram method gives that explanation.
      </p>
      <p>
        So the two methods have different strengths. Venn diagrams
        are slower but explanatory. Mood and figure are compact and
        text-based. Used together, they give you both the visual
        structure and the portable label for the same argument
        form.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-translating-arguments-into-syllogism-form">
    <title>Putting Prose Arguments into Syllogism Form</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        So far, most of our syllogisms have already been in
        standard form. Real arguments usually are not so obliging.
        They come as prose: sentences with <q>because,</q> unstated
        assumptions, ordinary verbs, pronouns, and terms that have
        to be made consistent before the Venn method can be used.
      </p>
      <p>
        The task is not to replace the original argument with a
        prettier argument. The task is to reconstruct the argument
        fairly enough that its categorical structure can be tested.
        A good reconstruction preserves what the passage is trying
        to prove while making the categories explicit.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-syllogism-reconstruction-procedure">
      <title>The procedure</title>
      <p>
        Use the reconstruction skills from Chapter 2 and the
        translation skills from Chapter 6 together.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Find the conclusion.</alert> Indicator words
            such as <q>so,</q> <q>therefore,</q> and <q>it follows
            that</q> help. So do premise indicators such as
            <q>because</q> and <q>since.</q>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Identify S and P from the conclusion.</alert>
            The conclusion's subject term is S. The conclusion's
            predicate term is P.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Find the middle term.</alert> The middle term M
            appears in the premises but not in the conclusion. It
            is the category that connects S to P.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Make the wording consistent.</alert> Use the
            same category term each time the argument is talking
            about the same class. This often means replacing a
            verb phrase with a noun phrase: <q>degrades human
            personality</q> becomes <q>laws that degrade human
            personality.</q>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Add only fair implicit premises.</alert> If the
            passage clearly relies on a missing categorical claim,
            make it explicit. Do not add a premise just to make a
            bad argument good.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <alert>Put the result in standard form.</alert> The
            major premise contains P and M. The minor premise
            contains S and M. The conclusion contains S and P.
            Then evaluate the syllogism by Venn diagram or by the
            modern-valid form table.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-paraphrase-boundaries">
      <title>Fair paraphrase</title>
      <p>
        Paraphrase is allowed because ordinary English is not built
        in categorical notation. <q>Fads aren't healthy</q> can be
        paraphrased as <q>No fads are healthy things.</q> <q>Anyone
        who is honest is naive</q> can be paraphrased as <q>All
        honest people are naive people.</q> <q>Only models trained
        on code can pass a coding interview</q> becomes <q>All
        things that can pass a coding interview are models trained
        on code.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        But the paraphrase has to preserve the argument's meaning.
        Do not strengthen a claim, weaken a claim, or quietly
        change the subject matter. <q>Some futurists believe that
        technology can solve all moral problems</q> does not become
        <q>All futurists believe that technology can solve all
        moral problems.</q> <q>People who get their news from
        social media miss what is actually happening</q> does not
        become <q>People who use social media are ignorant.</q>
        The categories may be cleaned up; the claim itself may not
        be improved.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-mlk-syllogism-reconstruction">
      <title>Worked example: Martin Luther King Jr.</title>
      <p>
        Consider this passage from <em>Letter from a Birmingham
        Jail</em>:
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <p>
          <q>Any law that degrades human personality is unjust.
          All segregation statutes are unjust because segregation
          distorts the soul and damages the personality.</q><fn>
            Martin Luther King Jr., <em>Letter from a Birmingham
            Jail</em>, 1963.
          </fn>
        </p>
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        The second sentence contains both the conclusion and the
        reason for it. The conclusion is that segregation statutes
        are unjust. The reason is that segregation degrades human
        personality. To put the passage into categorical form, we
        need the category terms to line up.
      </p>
      <p>
        The conclusion is:
      </p>
      <p>
        C: All segregation statutes are unjust laws.
      </p>
      <p>
        So S is <em>segregation statutes</em>, and P is
        <em>unjust laws</em>. The middle term is
        <em>laws that degrade human personality</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The standard-form syllogism is:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-mlk-standard-form-syllogism">
        <title>Segregation statutes</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: All laws that degrade human personality are unjust laws.</p>
          <p>P2: All segregation statutes are laws that degrade human personality.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: All segregation statutes are unjust laws.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This is a valid syllogism. In mood-and-figure notation, it
        has the form AAA-1, which appears in the modern-valid
        table. By Venn diagram, P1 shades the part of M outside P;
        P2 shades the part of S outside M. Together, those shadings
        shade all of S outside P, which is exactly what the
        conclusion requires.
      </p>
      <p>
        There is also a natural negative reconstruction of the same
        argument:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-mlk-obverse-standard-form-syllogism">
        <title>Segregation statutes, negative form</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: No laws that degrade human personality are just laws.</p>
          <p>P2: All segregation statutes are laws that degrade human personality.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: No segregation statutes are just laws.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This version is valid too: EAE-1. It is not a competing
        argument so much as a different categorical rendering of
        the same point. Its P1 and conclusion are effectively the
        obverses of the corresponding claims in the first
        reconstruction: <q>All M are unjust laws</q> becomes
        <q>No M are just laws,</q> and <q>All S are unjust laws</q>
        becomes <q>No S are just laws.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice the reconstructive choice. The original passage says
        that segregation distorts and damages personality. The
        syllogism treats segregation statutes as laws that degrade
        human personality. That is a fair paraphrase because it
        captures the role that sentence plays in the argument. It
        would not be fair to add a separate premise that all unjust
        laws must be disobeyed, because that is not the conclusion
        being tested here.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-enthymeme-example">
      <title>When a premise is missing</title>
      <p>
        Sometimes the passage gives a premise and a conclusion, but
        leaves out the general rule that would connect them:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-pro-life-legislation-enthymeme">
        <title>A missing premise</title>
        <statement>
          <p>All pro-life legislation restricts freedom.</p>
          <p>So, no pro-life legislation should be passed.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        As written, this is an enthymeme: a premise is unstated.
        The argument is relying on something like this:
      </p>
      <p>
        No legislation that restricts freedom is legislation that
        should be passed.
      </p>
      <p>
        With that premise made explicit, the standard-form
        syllogism is:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-pro-life-legislation-standard-form">
        <title>Restricting freedom</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: No legislation that restricts freedom is legislation that should be passed.</p>
          <p>P2: All pro-life legislation is legislation that restricts freedom.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: No pro-life legislation is legislation that should be passed.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The reconstructed syllogism is valid: EAE-1. But that does
        not settle whether the original argument is sound. It only
        tells us that if the stated premise and the implicit
        premise are true, the conclusion follows.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-particular-prose-example">
      <title>When the conclusion is particular</title>
      <p>
        Particular claims often hide inside ordinary phrases such
        as <q>there are,</q> <q>some,</q> or <q>according to this
        evidence, some.</q> Consider:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-futurists-standard-form">
        <title>Futurists</title>
        <statement>
          <p>Anyone who believes that technology can solve all moral problems is overly optimistic.</p>
          <p>According to surveys, some futurists believe that technology can solve all moral problems.</p>
          <p>It follows that there are futurists who are overly optimistic.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The conclusion is <q>Some futurists are overly optimistic
        people.</q> So S is <em>futurists</em> and P is
        <em>overly optimistic people</em>. The middle term is
        <em>people who believe that technology can solve all moral
        problems</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        In standard form:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-futurists-reconstructed-syllogism">
        <title>Technology and optimism</title>
        <statement>
          <p>P1: All people who believe that technology can solve all moral problems are overly optimistic people.</p>
          <p>P2: Some futurists are people who believe that technology can solve all moral problems.</p>
          <p><m>\therefore</m> C: Some futurists are overly optimistic people.</p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This is valid: AII-1. The particular premise places an X
        in the S-and-M region. The universal premise forces any
        such X into P. The conclusion needs an X in S-and-P, and
        the premise diagram supplies it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-not-every-passage-fits">
      <title>Not every passage fits</title>
      <p>
        The categorical syllogism is a powerful form, but it is
        still only one form. Some arguments need conditionals,
        disjunctions, causal claims, probabilities, or more than
        three category terms. Do not force every passage into a
        syllogism.
      </p>
      <p>
        A passage is a good candidate for categorical reconstruction
        when it has three recurring categories and the conclusion
        relates two of them. If you need four or five categories to
        state the argument honestly, or if the argument turns on
        <q>if ... then</q> structure rather than category inclusion
        or exclusion, save it for another logical tool.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-7-5-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Syllogize a real argument</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a short argument in an editorial, speech, essay, or
          other source that looks like it might have a syllogistic
          structure — three terms, two premises, a conclusion. Follow
          the procedure from this section: identify the three terms,
          arrange the premises, supply any missing premise, and put
          it in standard form. Then diagram it. Is the resulting
          syllogism valid?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-categorical-syllogisms-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <p>
      Categorical logic gives us one formal machine for testing
      validity. If an argument can be reconstructed as a
      three-term syllogism, then the Venn method gives a precise
      answer to the validity question: the argument is valid if
      the premise diagram already contains what the conclusion
      claims.
    </p>
    <p>
      But categorical logic does not cover every valid argument.
      Some arguments turn on the internal structure of whole
      sentences rather than on relations among categories. Consider
      the difference between these two patterns:
    </p>
    <p>
      All M are P. All S are M. Therefore, all S are P.
    </p>
    <p>
      If P, then Q. P. Therefore, Q.
    </p>
    <p>
      The first is categorical. It works by relating classes. The
      second is sentential. It works by relating whole statements.
      The next part of the book turns to that second kind of
      structure: conditionals, disjunctions, negations,
      conjunctions, and the rules that govern them.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is not a rejection of categorical logic. It is an
      expansion of the toolkit. Part II taught one disciplined way
      to ask whether a conclusion follows from premises. Part III
      gives us another, better suited to arguments whose logical
      force depends on words such as <q>if,</q> <q>not,</q>
      <q>and,</q> and <q>or.</q>
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch7">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter combined categorical propositions into
      categorical syllogisms and tested them for validity. The
      core ideas, section by section:
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Standard Form Syllogisms (§7.1).</alert> A categorical
      syllogism has two premises and a conclusion, all in
      standard-form categorical propositions, using exactly three
      terms: S, P, and M. The conclusion determines S and P; the
      remaining term is M.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Diagramming a Syllogism (§7.2).</alert> The premises
      go on a three-circle Venn diagram. The conclusion is tested
      against the premise diagram. The syllogism is valid when the
      premise diagram already contains what the conclusion claims.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Common Validity Patterns and Failure Points (§7.3).</alert>
      Some invalid syllogisms fail because a required region is not
      shaded, because an X remains on a boundary, or because
      universal premises provide no existential commitment. The
      ozone example shows why some traditionally valid forms are
      invalid on the modern interpretation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Mood and Figure (§7.4).</alert> Mood records the A, E,
      I, O sequence of the major premise, minor premise, and
      conclusion. Figure records the position of the middle term.
      Together, mood and figure give a compact text label for a
      syllogism.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Putting Prose Arguments into Syllogism Form (§7.5).</alert>
      Real arguments often need reconstruction before they can be
      tested. The fair task is to identify the conclusion, fix the
      category terms, add only legitimate implicit premises, put
      the argument in standard form, and then evaluate it.
    </p>

    <p>
      <alert>Where We're Headed (§7.6).</alert> Categorical logic
      handles arguments about classes. Part III turns to
      sentential logic, where validity depends on the structure of
      whole statements.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch7-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-boundary-x">
        <title>Boundary X</title>
        <p>An X placed on a boundary between regions because the relevant particular claim does not yet determine which region contains the object. (§7.2, §7.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-categorical-syllogism">
        <title>Categorical syllogism</title>
        <p>A three-statement argument with two premises and a conclusion, all standard-form categorical propositions, using exactly three terms. (§7.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-enthymeme">
        <title>Enthymeme</title>
        <p>An argument with an unstated premise or conclusion. In syllogism reconstruction, fair implicit premises may be made explicit. (§7.5)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-figure">
        <title>Figure</title>
        <p>The arrangement of the middle term in the major and minor premises of a categorical syllogism. (§7.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-major-premise">
        <title>Major premise</title>
        <p>The premise containing the major term P and the middle term M. (§7.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-major-term">
        <title>Major term</title>
        <p>The predicate term of the conclusion, represented by P. (§7.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-middle-term">
        <title>Middle term</title>
        <p>The term that appears in both premises but not in the conclusion, represented by M. (§7.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-minor-premise">
        <title>Minor premise</title>
        <p>The premise containing the minor term S and the middle term M. (§7.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-minor-term">
        <title>Minor term</title>
        <p>The subject term of the conclusion, represented by S. (§7.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-mood">
        <title>Mood</title>
        <p>The sequence of A, E, I, and O forms in a syllogism's major premise, minor premise, and conclusion. (§7.4)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-standard-form-syllogism">
        <title>Standard form syllogism</title>
        <p>A categorical syllogism arranged with the major premise first, the minor premise second, and the conclusion last. (§7.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch7-validity-table">
        <title>Validity table</title>
        <p>A list of mood-and-figure forms that are valid on the modern interpretation. (§7.4)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch7">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch7-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Terms and Standard Form</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each syllogism, identify S, P, and M. Then rewrite
          the argument in standard form: major premise, minor
          premise, conclusion.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s01-01"><statement><p>All journalists are people who ask inconvenient questions. No campaign surrogates are journalists. So, no campaign surrogates are people who ask inconvenient questions.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s01-02"><statement><p>Some federal judges are former prosecutors. All former prosecutors are lawyers. Therefore, some federal judges are lawyers.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s01-03"><statement><p>No successful scams are transparent business practices. Some online investment schemes are successful scams. So, some online investment schemes are not transparent business practices.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s01-04"><statement><p>All data centers are heavy users of electricity. Some heavy users of electricity are not good fits for weak power grids. Therefore, some good fits for weak power grids are not data centers.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch7-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Venn-Diagram Validity</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each syllogism is already in standard form. Evaluate it
          for validity on the modern interpretation using a
          three-circle Venn diagram. State whether it is valid or
          invalid.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s02-01"><statement><p>No right-wing hate mongers are socialists. Some Americans are socialists. Therefore, some Americans are not right-wing hate mongers.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s02-02"><statement><p>No vegetarians are meat eaters. No consistent thinkers are meat eaters. Therefore, all consistent thinkers are vegetarians.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s02-03"><statement><p>All Kilgore Trout stories are works of neglected genius. Some works of neglected genius are not widely read books. Therefore, some widely read books are not Kilgore Trout stories.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s02-04"><statement><p>All ozone molecules are good absorbers of UV rays. All ozone molecules are substances destroyed by chlorine. Therefore, some substances destroyed by chlorine are good absorbers of UV rays.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s02-05"><statement><p>All people who read carefully are people who notice hidden assumptions. Some students are people who read carefully. Therefore, some students are people who notice hidden assumptions.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch7-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Mood and Figure</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each standard-form syllogism, identify its mood and
          figure. Then use the modern-valid form table to say
          whether it is valid.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s03-01"><statement><p>No M are P. All S are M. Therefore, no S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s03-02"><statement><p>All P are M. No S are M. Therefore, no S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s03-03"><statement><p>All M are P. All M are S. Therefore, some S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s03-04"><statement><p>Some M are P. All M are S. Therefore, some S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s03-05"><statement><p>No P are M. Some S are M. Therefore, some S are not P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s03-06"><statement><p>All P are M. Some M are S. Therefore, some S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch7-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Putting Prose into Syllogism Form</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Translate each prose argument into a standard-form
          categorical syllogism. Add only fair implicit premises.
          Then evaluate for validity on the modern interpretation.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s04-01"><statement><p>Anyone who believes that technology can solve all moral problems is overly optimistic. Some futurists believe that technology can solve all moral problems. It follows that some futurists are overly optimistic.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s04-02"><statement><p>Fads are not healthy things. Every crash diet is a fad. So, crash diets are not healthy things.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s04-03"><statement><p>People who get their news only from social media miss important context. Those who miss important context are poorly informed. Therefore, people who get their news only from social media are poorly informed.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s04-04"><statement><p>All pro-life legislation restricts freedom. So, no pro-life legislation should be passed.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s04-05"><statement><p>Every law that degrades human personality is unjust. Segregation statutes degrade human personality. Therefore, segregation statutes are unjust.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch7-s05">
      <title>Exercise Set 5: Explaining Invalidity</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each syllogism is invalid on the modern interpretation.
          Explain the failure point in words: missing shading,
          missing X, boundary X, two negative premises, two
          particular premises, or existential import.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s05-01"><statement><p>No M are P. No S are M. Therefore, all S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s05-02"><statement><p>All M are P. All M are S. Therefore, some S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s05-03"><statement><p>Some M are not P. Some M are S. Therefore, some S are not P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s05-04"><statement><p>All P are M. Some S are not M. Therefore, some S are not P.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s05-05"><statement><p>Some P are M. Some S are M. Therefore, some S are P.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch7-s06">
      <title>Exercise Set 6: Mixed Review</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each item, do whatever is needed: identify terms,
          put the argument in standard form, diagram it or identify
          mood and figure, and evaluate for validity.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s06-01"><statement><p>No AI safety researchers are accelerationists. All people calling for slower deployment are AI safety researchers. Therefore, no people calling for slower deployment are accelerationists.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s06-02"><statement><p>Only models trained on code can pass a coding interview. Some chatbots can pass coding interviews. Therefore, some chatbots are models trained on code.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s06-03"><statement><p>No non-voters are people who returned a ballot. Some eligible citizens are non-voters. Therefore, some eligible citizens are not people who returned a ballot.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s06-04"><statement><p>All laws identical to this ordinance are laws that restrict camping downtown. No laws that restrict camping downtown are laws supported by the housing coalition. Therefore, no laws identical to this ordinance are laws supported by the housing coalition.</p></statement></exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-s06-05"><statement><p>Some committee reports are not public documents. All committee reports are records produced by the council. Therefore, some records produced by the council are not public documents.</p></statement></exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch7-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt connects to Field Exercise 7-1.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch7-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Reflect on your experience in Field Exercise 7-1. Did
            forcing the argument into syllogistic form require you to
            distort the arguer's intent? Was the translation a fair
            representation of what the arguer meant, or did the
            categorical framework squeeze out something important?
            Write a short response considering both what the
            syllogistic form <em>reveals</em> about the argument and
            what it might <em>obscure</em>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
